# Git workflow — Awesome Soundboard

After completing a requested code or config change, **commit and push by default** unless the user explicitly says not to.

## When to commit and push

Do both after:
- Bug fixes, features, or refactors
- Cursor rule / docs / workflow updates
- Any change the user asked to implement

Skip commit/push only when the user says:
- "don't commit", "no commit", "don't push", or similar
- The task is read-only (questions, reviews, explanations only)

## Commit protocol

1. Run `git status`, `git diff`, and `git log -3 --oneline` before committing
2. Stage only relevant files; never commit `.env` or secrets
3. Write a concise message focused on **why** (1–2 sentences)
4. Push to `origin` after a successful commit

## PowerShell note

This repo is developed on Windows. Use `;` instead of `&&` in shell commands, and pass multi-line commit messages with `-m` flags (heredocs are not supported in PowerShell).

## Deploy side effect

Pushing to `main` triggers the CapRover deploy workflow (`.github/workflows/deploy.yml`).
